Photo: Jamaal Ellis, For The Chronicle Marina and the Diamonds performs at Revention Music Center in... Image 51 of 51 Marina and the Diamonds shines in Houston 1 / 51 Back to Gallery Marina Diamandis is an electro-pop superstar. And it's time for the U.S. to catch up.
The cheeky singer and songwriter kicked off her Neon Nature Tour on Monday night at Revention Music Center. The venue was solidly packed but not completely full. Her engaging, effervescent sound, however, is worthy of a stadium.
Diamandis has a unique allure that connected strongly with every fan inside the venue. There's '80s and indie pop, Tori Amos and Kate Bush, Madonna and Donna Summer in what she does. It all comes alive effortlessly onstage.
Diamandis split the show into three parts, named for her albums: "The Family Jewels," "Electra Heart" and this year's "Froot." Her band was on risers just above her.
Setlist "Mowgli's Road"
"I Am Not a Robot"
"Oh No!"
"Obsessions"
"Hollywood"
"Bubblegum Bitch"
"Radioactive"
"How to be a Heartbreaker"
"Primadonna"
"The State of Dreaming"
"Froot"
"Forget"
"Savages"
"Happy"
"Can't Pin Me Down"
"I'm a Ruin"
"Blue"
"Immortal"
The Diamonds in her stage name — Marina and the Diamonds — refers to her fans. They sang "Happy Birthday" near the end of the night. (She turned 30 Saturday.)
A bit of Kanye West/Jay-Z tune "No Church in the Wild" preceded her entrance. The show itself was an explosion of neon, sparkly costumes and frothy energy. Emojis and Betty Boop cartoons swirled on screens behind her.
"The Family Jewels" segment was sweeping and sincere, from opener "Mowgli's Road" to the solemn "Obsessions." It segued into the "Electra Heart" era, which pulsed with dancefloor ferocity. Every song here was a hands-in-the-air standout: "Bubblegum Bitch," "Radioactive," "How to be a Heartbreaker."
Diamandis has a voice that goes from flirty and cooing to big and wailing. She lifted every song into the heavens.
The final stretch, "Froot," was awash in dreamy synth-pop. She joked through a cape mishap and a minor lyrical slip, enlisting the crowd to help with the words. It just made her more endearing. Sweet ballad "Happy" had the crowd swaying back and forth. "Immortal" was a truly stunning closer.
Diamandis has said she doesn't care if she gets another fan and is happy with her career trajectory. But the urgency and energy she puts into every moment deserves some major-league love.
